23_0	0.0	PURCELLVILLE, Va.
23_1	0.0	_ The dormitories are still under construction in the hilly fields, but Patrick Henry College already has a few rules: Students will wear uniforms.
23_2	0.0	They won't drink.
23_3	0.0	They won't date, unless their parents ``are informed of the potential romance'' and approve.
23_4	0.0	All of which will set the college apart when it opens next fall.
23_5	0.09090909090909091	Yet what is drawing national attention to the school is not its strict code of conduct, but its future student body.
23_6	0.0	Almost every undergraduate entering Patrick Henry College will have been home-schooled.
23_7	0.0	That makes them graduates of one of the most controversial movements in American education, one that gained steam in the 1980s amid a series of legal battles pitting parents against the government.
23_8	0.23529411764705882	Now that the first wave of the country's 1.5 million home-schooled children is reaching college age, there is a new debate: When, and how, should they be thrust into the ``real world''?
23_9	0.36363636363636365	Critics of home-schooling have long argued children need exposure to the outside world and peers to grow into well-rounded adults.
23_10	0.0	And home-schoolers freely admit their aim is to ``let children be children'' by sheltering them from the harsh realities and temptations of the modern world.
23_11	0.0	But when do children stop being children?
23_12	0.0	How do they make that transition?
23_13	0.42857142857142855	And what kind of adult lives will home-schooled children be prepared to lead?
23_14	0.0	Officials at Patrick Henry College, believed to be the first ever to target home-schoolers, think they have found an answer in their curriculum: The only major for incoming freshmen will be government.
23_15	0.0	In addition to their classes, students will write legislative papers for US congressmen, which they hope will then be used as actual guides for congressional staffers.
23_16	0.0	Students will also participate in Capitol Hill ``apprenticeships,'' all to train them for a future in the most unsheltered of careers: politics.
23_17	0.07692307692307693	``If the real world means Capitol Hill, they'll be as prepared as anyone,'' said the school's founder, Michael P.
23_18	0.0	Farris, who has home-schooled his 10 children, the oldest of whom is 24.
23_19	0.0	``If it is defined as the college bar scene?
23_20	0.0	No, they're not going to be prepared for that a bit.
23_21	0.0	It would be fair to say we're skipping one phase of wildness.
23_22	0.0	We're skipping them straight into adulthood''.
23_23	0.23076923076923078	This intertwining of politics and home-schooled students is bound to draw notice, especially since the home-schooling movement is so often depicted as antigovernment.
23_24	1.4375	In the last 19 years advocates for home schooling have filed hundreds of lawsuits in more than 40 states, according to the Home School Legal Defense Association.
23_25	0.0	The purpose of the litigation, in most cases, has been to get government out of citizens' educational lives.
23_26	0.0	But to Farris and his colleagues, the vision is entirely consistent.
